== Final years ==

Mack released his final album, ''Lonnie Mack Live: Attack of the Killer V'', in 1990, but continued to perform, mostly in small venues, into the early 2000s. His last commercial performances were in 2004.<ref>The photo accompanying this article is from a performance during that season.</ref> Although he soon found that he "miss[ed] the stage, performing, and making people happy",<ref>"Unsung Guitar Hero: Lonnie Mack" (http://www.gibson.com/News-Lifestyle/Features/en-us/Unsung-Guitar-Hero-Lon{{dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} nie-Mack.aspx). gibson.com. Retrieved November 29, 2017.</ref> he remained retired except for a handful of isolated special appearances over the next few years:

On February 17, 2007, he performed "Cincinnati Jail" at a Nashville organ-transplant benefit concert for [[Pure Prairie League]] singer-bassist Michael Reilly.<ref>"Photo of Mack playing at concert" (https://web.archive.org/web/20110715132351/http://pureprairieleague.com/benefit/index. htm). Pureprairieleague.com. Archived from the original (http://pureprairieleague.com/benefit/index.htm) on July 15, 2011. Retrieved July 27, 2011. In 2020, Reilly credited Mack with inspiring him to become a musician. Spotlight Central, "Bustin Out! Spotlight on Pure Prairie League's Mike Reilly", New Jersey Stage, July 14, 2020, at https://www.newjerseystage.com/articles/getarticle.php?titlelink=bustin-out-spotlight-on-pure-prairie-leagues-mike-reilly; Garret K. Woodward, "The attitude of gratitude: Michael Reilly of Pure Prairie League", Smoky Mountain News, June 22, 2021, at https://smokymountainnews.com/archives/item/31620-the-attitude-of-gratitude-michael-reilly-of-pure-prairie-league</ref> On November 15, 2008, he performed "Wham!" at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]]'s 93rd birthday salute to electric guitar pioneer, [[Les Paul]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Official Rock Hall Blog |url=https://rockhallandmuseum.blogspot.com |access-date=2022-07-29 |website=rockhallandmuseum.blogspot.com}}</ref> Later in the evening, he participated in a blues jam with Les Paul and a lineup of prominent rock guitarists.<ref name="cleveland.com">{{cite web|author=John Soeder, ''The Plain Dealer''|url=http://www.cleveland.com/music/index.ssf/2008/11/guitar_stars_pay_tribute_to_le.html|title=Guitar stars pay tribute to Les Paul in Cleveland concert|website=Cleveland.com|date=November 16, 2008|access-date=July 27, 2011}} These included [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], [[Billy Gibbons]], [[Richie Sambora]], [[Duane Eddy]], [[James Burton]], [[Dennis Coffey]], [[Jeff "Skunk" Baxter]], [[Jennifer Batten]], and [[Steve Lukather]].</ref>

On April 4, 2009, at age 67, he spontaneously took the stage at a rural Tennessee roadhouse, performing "Cincinnati Jail" with an electric guitar borrowed from the house band's lead player, who wrote:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thegearpage.net/board/index.php?threads/lonnie-mack-sat-in-with-my-band-sat-night.532235/|title=Lonnie Mack sat in with my band Sat night...|website=Thegearpage.net|date=April 6, 2009 |access-date=August 28, 2018}}</ref>

{{blockquote | He made a couple of adjustments and then proceeded to begin OFFICIALLY TEARING THE ROOF OFF THE PLACE. He peeled the paint off the walls with my rig. His (my?) guitar was smoking. Sounded like the breathing of a very large, wild animal. His band leading skills were also awesome. Lots of pointing at people to change dynamics and cue solos. He owned the stage and had everybody doing exactly what he wanted them to do. Crowd went nuts, people were taking pics with their camera phones. People were screaming, everybody started dancing, it was great. He cut my other lead player's head clean off when they were swapping licks, [which] was pretty funny, as [my other lead player] is a big [[Eddie Van Halen]]-style flash player. Bottom line – His playing is still awesome. Tone is very much in the fingers. He made my rig absolutely come alive in ways I've never heard.}}

In 2010, again with a borrowed guitar, he performed "Memphis" at the final reunion of his "Memphis"-era band.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=April 8, 2014 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=utqP7q244mY |title="Memphis" with Lonnie Mack and Gene Lawson (original drummer) |publisher=Lawson Microphones |via=[[YouTube]] |access-date=October 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211012143507/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=utqP7q244mY |archive-date=October 12, 2021 |url-status=live}}</ref> There is no account of Mack performing thereafter.

In 2011, he released a handful of kitchen-table acoustic recordings via the internet.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=June 20, 2011 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wOSCnUTb7Ds |title=The Times Ain't Right.rzmmpj.mp4 |publisher=Lonnie Mack |via=[[YouTube]] |access-date=October 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624162813/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wOSCnUTb7Ds&gl=US&hl=en |archive-date=June 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |date=August 2, 2011 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wNrwmsE521s |title=You Need A Little Help 1 |publisher=Lonnie Mack |via=[[YouTube]] |access-date=October 26, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200624162817/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wNrwmsE521s&gl=US&hl=en |archive-date=June 24, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> About that time, he was also reportedly working on a memoir<ref>"Lonnie Mack Comes Back to Life" (http://rockabillyhall.com/NewsArch02.html). Rockabillyhall.com. Retrieved July 27, 2011.</ref> and engaged in a songwriting collaboration with award-winning country and blues tunesmith Bobby Boyd.<ref>"Bobby Boyd profile at" (https://web.archive.org/web/20110708075009/http://www.bobbyboydband.com/bio.html). Bobbyboydband.com. Archived from the original (http://www.bobbyboydband.com/bio.html) on July 8, 2011. Retrieved July 27, 2011.</ref>

In 2012, early rock guitar sensation [[Travis Wammack]] asked Mack to join him on a proposed tour to be billed as "Double Mack Attack". Mack declined, saying that he "...wasn't in good shape. He said he can't play standing up any more [and] it's hard to hold a Flying V sitting down."<ref>{{Cite web |last=Writer |first=Russ Corey Staff |title=Shoals musicians recall Lonnie Mack as great guitarist, singer |url=https://www.timesdaily.com/news/shoals-musicians-recall-lonnie-mack-as-great-guitarist-singer/article_48a46f3e-8dae-5334-a3c7-1a6ec1260060.html |access-date=2022-07-29 |website=TimesDaily |date=April 23, 2016 |language=en}}</ref>

Mack died from natural causes on April 21, 2016 (age 74) at Centennial Medical Center, Nashville, Tennessee.<ref>Martin Kielty, "Guitar pioneer Lonnie Mack dies at 74", April 22, 2916, Classic Rock – The Home of High Voltage Rock'N'Roll", at https://www.loudersound.com/news/lonnie-mack-guitar-poineer-dead-74</ref> In the media, his death was overshadowed by that of rock superstar [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], who died on the same day.<ref name="McArdle" />

